%claude:
This appendix has two purposes. First, it is a concrete
example of a literate program---a complement to
Section~\ref{sec:literate-programming},
which presented literate programming in the abstract.
%
Reading the source of a real program presented in literate form is the best
way to see what literate programming actually buys you.
%and to learn the [[noweb/syncweb]]
%conventions (\verb+<<chunk name>>=+, \verb+@+, and
%\verb+[[code]]+ for inline code references) by example.
%
Second, it is a full explanation of a real \plan program: 
[[ed]], which is small enough (under 1700~lines of C) to
fit in one appendix, yet old enough and famous enough
that almost every modern editors and string-processing tools
descend from it in some way.
%
Reading its source code is a quick way to see how a
non-trivial \unix tool was structured in the 1970s.

%padism:
Note that the original source code of [[ed]] has been slightly modified to
be arguably easier to read. Moreover, in addition to my explanations,
I have also sometimes added a few comments in the code itself.
%
The original comments from Ken Thompson are using
the standard C syntax [[/**/]] while my comments are using
the [[//]] syntax, so they are easy to differentiate.

