\subsection{A line editor}

[[ed]], short for ``editor''\footnote{
  \plan and \unix authors did like short command names: 
  [[ed]], [[mk]], [[rc]], [[db]], [[ls]], etc.},
is one of the oldest \unix programs,
originally written by Ken Thompson in the 1970s.
%(part of the special "3 weeks" where he wrote editor, assembler, kernel?)
%
It is a {\em line editor}: rather than always displaying a file content
on {screen} like [[vi]], Emacs, or \plan's [[sam]] and [[acme]],
[[ed]] works mostly one line at a time, accepting commands from standard input
and printing results to standard output (possibly displaying lines of the
edited file depending on the input commands).
%claude:
This makes it look primitive compared to modern {\em screen editors},
but it has a crucial advantage: it can be {scripted}.
You can pipe a sequence of editing commands into [[ed]] from a shell
script, something that is awkward or impossible with most editors.
%said-later: see mkenam in plan9 code.
%Also if need quick and dirty write a file with a few lines => ed!
% See also \book{Editor} for screen editor.
% edit just one file at a time.

%claude:
While you can already create and modify files using [[echo]] and shell
redirection ([[>]], [[>>]]), [[ed]] offers far more power: searching,
substituting, moving lines, and operating on {ranges} of lines.
%
For a quick hands-on feel, here is a complete [[ed]] session:

\label{sec:ed-tutorial-session}
\begin{verbatim}
   $ ed
   i
   hello
   world
   .
   1,2p
   hello
   world
   f hello.txt
   hello.txt
   w
   12
   q
   $ cat hello.txt
   hello
   world
   $
\end{verbatim}

%claude:
The session above launches [[ed]], starts {\em insert mode} with [[i]],
types two lines, ends the insertion with a single [['.']] on its own
line, prints lines~1 to~2 with [[1,2p]] made of an {\em address range}
and the [[p]] command ([[ed]] echoes the 2 lines),
sets the {\em remembered filename} with [[f hello.txt]] ([[ed]] echoes it
back), saves the {\em buffer} with [[w]] ([[ed]] echoes the character count
written), and finally quits with [[q]].
%alt: use special color for what is entered and what is echoed? or > ?

%claude:
[[ed]] is famously silent: it prints no prompt, and every line
you type is either a command or part of a text-entry session
opened by [[i]] (or [[a]] for {\em append mode}).
%
For a full tutorial introduction to [[ed]], see Appendix~1 of
``The \unix Programming Environment'' \cite{unix-pike},
or Kernighan's two tutorials from the Bell Labs technical reports.
See also the man page of [[ed]] at [[docs/man/1/ed]] in my \plan repository.

%claude:
Note that many ideas that seem to ``belong'' to other tools actually originated in
[[ed]]: the [[s/re/replacement/]] syntax used by [[sed]], the [[g/re/p]]
command that gave [[grep]] its name (``global regular expression print''),
and commands like [[w]], [[q]], [[a]], [[i]] that [[vi]] inherited directly.
%
It is thus interesting to see the code of the program
that started it all.
%Moreover, editor is a fundamental program, see other appendix.


\subsection{A scriptable editor}
\label{sec:motivations-mkenam}
%alt: \subsection{Motivations: [[mkenam]]}
%spirit: give desire to learn ed! quite cool tool actually, I've learned stuff!

%claude:
Here is a real example of [[ed]] used as a code generator during
the build of \plan.
%
The [[mkenam]] script below transforms a header file
([[5.out.h]]) containing assembler opcode definitions into a C
source file ([[enam.c]]) containing a string array of opcode names:

<<mkenam>>=
ed - ../5l/5.out.h <<'!'
v/^	A/d
1,$s/^	A/	"/
g/ .*$/s///
,s/,*$/",/
1i
char*	anames[] =
{
.
$a
};
.
w enam.c
Q
!
@
%alt: could be simplified, see my simpler xix/tests/ed/mkenam.sh
% no need 'g/ .*$/s///',   I replaced some  ',s/.../' by clearer '1,$s/.../',
% the last 'Q' could be a 'q'

To understand what this script does, it helps to see
a concrete example of input and output.
%claude:
Here is what a snippet of
the input file [[5.out.h]] looks like (left) and what
the output [[enam.c]] is supposed to look like (right):

%example:
\begin{vdiagram}
   5.out.h (input)            enam.c (generated output)
   ----------------           ---------------------------
   enum    As {               char* anames[] =
       AXXX,                   {
       ANOP,                       "XXX",
       AAND,                       "NOP",
       AORR,                       "AND",
       AEOR,                       "ORR",
       AADD,                       "EOR",
       ASUB,                       "ADD",
       ...                         "SUB",
   };                              ...
                              };
\end{vdiagram}


The transformations from [[5.out.h]] to [[enam.c]] are: 
keep only lines starting with a tab followed by [[A]] (the opcode names),
remove that prefix [[A]],
wrap each name in double quotes followed by a comma, and
add the \verb+char* anames[]+ array header and enclosing braces.
%
Each time someone modifies [[5.out.h]], the [[enam.c]] can be regenerated
automatically thanks to the [[mkenam]] script called from [[5c/mkfile]].

%claude:
The [[mkenam]] script uses [[ed -]] (quiet mode, suppressing character counts)
and a shell here-document ([[<<'!']], see the \book{Shell}) to feed commands.
% '-' suppress counts by e/r/w and remove verbose/interactive mode (default)
%alt: could store ed script in separate file instead of using <<
%
It first deletes lines not starting with [[A]] ([[v/^	A/d]]),
then uses [[s///]] substitutions to reshape each remaining line
into a quoted C string, and finally uses [[i]] ([[1i]], meaning insert back at line 1) and [[a]] ([[$a]], meaning appending at the end)
to wrap the result with the array declaration.
%
By the end of this appendix, you will fully understand every command in
this script (and the code behind those commands).

%claude:
The key advantage of [[ed]] here is that the editing commands are
plain text, easily embedded in a shell script or a [[mkfile]] rule.
%other:
Try doing the same in Emacs or Visual Studio Code---you would need an Emacs Lisp
program or complex key-sequence macro recording which would not be so easy
and fast to replay than [[mkenam]].
