\subsection{Line input and output buffers: [[line]] and [[linebuf]]}

%claude:
There are two distinct line buffers, which can be confusing.
%
[<line>] (70 bytes of [[char]]) is a small output buffer used by
[<putchr()>] to batch [[write()]] system calls--- UTF-8 encoded 
characters accumulate in [[line]] and are flushed when a newline
is encountered or the buffer is nearly full.
%
[<linebuf>] ([[LBSIZE]] entries of [[Rune]]) is the main working
buffer where a single line of edited text is held in Rune form.
%
Functions like [<getfile()>] fill [[linebuf]] from the input file,
[<putline()>] writes it to [[tfile]], and [<getline()>] reads it back.
%
The distinction between [[char]] for UTF-8 I/O and [[Rune]] for text
manipulation runs throughout the code.

<<globals ed.c>>=
char    line[70];
// ref<char> in line (mark end of line usually)
char*   linp    = line;
@
% why 70? 80 seems better to match number of columns in classic editors/terminals.

<<constants ed.c>>=
LBSIZE  = 4096,     /* max line size */
@
<<globals ed.c>>=
Rune    linebuf[LBSIZE];
@
% different from line[], here we have Rune[] not char[]


%said-before: figure with all those data structures

\subsection{Other globals: [[count]], [[col]], etc.}

%claude:
[<count>] is a general-purpose counter, most often used to track
the number of characters read or written (displayed by [<exfile()>]
in verbose mode).
%
[<col>] tracks the current output column, used by the [[l]] (list)
command to wrap long lines (see Section~\ref{sec:command-l}).

<<globals ed.c>>=
long count;
@

<<globals ed.c>>=
int col;
@


%******************************************************************************
\section{[[main()]]}
%******************************************************************************
%alt: main, init, quit

%trans:
I now switch from the bottom-up approach of the previous section
to a top-down approach, starting with [[main()]], the entry point of [[ed]].
%claude:
The [[main()]] function initializes
buffered console I/O with [[Binit()]]
(see the \book{Libcore} with the [[libbio]] library
and its [[Biobuf]] data structure),
installs a signal handler (called notes in \plan) with [[notify()]],
processes command-line flags, 
allocates [<zero>],
and finally
executes the main sequence: [<init()>][[;]] [<commands()>][[;]] [<quit()>].

<<globals ed.c>>=
// console buffered input
Biobuf  bcons;
@


<<function [[main]](ed.c)>>=
void
main(int argc, char *argv[])
{
    char *p1, *p2;

    Binit(&bcons, STDIN, OREAD);
    notify(notifyf);

    ARGBEGIN {
    <<[[main()]](ed.c) flags processing cases>>
    } ARGEND

    USED(argc);
    <<[[main()]](ed.c) if [[-]] flag>>
    <<[[main()]](ed.c) if [[oflag]]>>
    else if(*argv) {
        p1 = *argv;
        p2 = savedfile;
        while(*p2++ = *p1++)
            if(p2 >= &savedfile[sizeof(savedfile)])
                p2--;
        globp = L"r";
    }
    zero = malloc((nlall+5)*sizeof(int*)); // BUG should be sizeof(int)
    tfname = mktemp(template);

    init();
    <<[[main()]](ed.c) before [[commands()]]>>
    commands();
    quit();
}
@
%bugfix:
% was '... * sizeof(int*)' but should be sizeof(int)!
% yes! BUG! even Ken Thompson wrote buggy C code :)
%The +5 is just for sentinel and safe margin; it should really be +2 at max.


%claude:
The most tricky part in [[main()]] above is the [[globp = L"r"]] line.
When a filename argument is given (e.g., [[ed foo.txt]]),
the filename is copied into [<savedfile>] and [<globp>] is set
to the Unicode string [["r"]].
%
The [[L""]] prefix is standard C syntax for a {\em wide-string literal}
(see the \book{Compiler}):
where the bare [["r"]] would be a [[char*]] (one byte plus a null
terminator), [[L"r"]] is a [[Rune*]]---one [[Rune]] holding the
codepoint for [['r']] followed by a null [[Rune]] terminator.
%claude:
Later, when [<commands()>] calls [<getchr()>] to read user input, it will read from
[<globp>] before reading from the console, so the first command
executed is automatically~[[r]]---as if the user had typed
[[r foo.txt]].
%
This elegant trick avoids duplicating file-reading logic in [[main()]].
% but why use Rune* for globp? why not char*? all commands are ASCII anyway.
% actually some commands could be UTF8 since user input, so better be consistent

%claude: %bugfix:
The [[sizeof(int*)]] in the [[zero = malloc(...)]] line above is actually
a bug---it should be [[sizeof(int)]], since [[zero]] holds [[int]]
file offsets, not pointers. The bug is harmless on architectures
where pointers and integers have the same size (32-bit systems);
on 64-bit systems, pointers are 8~bytes while [[int]] is still 4,
so the allocation simply over-reserves memory without causing any
incorrect behavior.
%
Even Ken Thompson wrote slightly buggy C code.

\subsection{[[ed -]] and [[vflag]]}

%claude:
By default [[ed]] is verbose\footnote{
  verbose is a strong word for [[ed]]; even in verbose mode, [[ed]] remains
  very terse (to not say cryptic).}
([[vflag = true]]):
it prints character counts after [[r]] and [[w]] operations
(as shown in the [[ed]] session in Section~\ref{sec:ed-tutorial-session}).
%
The [[-]] flag (as in [[ed - foo.txt]]) suppresses this,
which is what you want when [[ed]] is driven by a script
(as in the [[mkenam]] example in Section~\ref{sec:motivations-mkenam}).

<<globals ed.c>>=
// verbose (a.k.a. interactive) mode
bool vflag   = true;
@
%padism: using bool and true/false, not int for everything

<<[[main()]](ed.c) if [[-]] flag>>=
if(*argv && (strcmp(*argv, "-") == 0)) {
    argv++;
    vflag = false;
}
@
%padism: was ORD__EQ at some point

\subsection{[[ed -o]] and [[oflag]]}

%claude:
The [[-o]] flag turns [[ed]] into a {\em filter} (see \book{Utilities}):
it sets [<savedfile>]
to [[/fd/1]] (\plan's path for stdout), so that [[w]] writes
to standard output instead of a file.
%
It also sets [[globp = L"a"]] to start this time in {\em append mode},
and disables verbose output (since character counts would corrupt
the output stream).

<<globals ed.c>>=
// output to standard output (instead of editing a file).
// Useful when ed is used as a filter.
bool oflag;
@

<<[[main()]](ed.c) flags processing cases>>=
case 'o':
    oflag = true;
    vflag = false;
    break;
@


<<[[main()]](ed.c) if [[oflag]]>>=
if(oflag) {
    p1 = "/fd/1";
    p2 = savedfile;
    while(*p2++ = *p1++)
        ;
    globp = L"a";
}
@


\subsection{[[mktemp()]]}

%claude:
[<mktemp()>] called early in [[main()]] generates a unique temporary
filename by replacing
the trailing [[X]]'s in the template parameter with the process ID digits.
%
If the resulting file already exists, it tries replacing the first
digit with [[a]], [[b]], etc.

<<globals ed.c>>=
// in Linux pid can be very long, so better to have at least 6 X (was 5 before)
// the mkstemp Linux man page recommends 6 X
char template[] = "/tmp/eXXXXXX";
@
%bugfix: I've used 6 so goken ed works under Linux

%ex: mktemp("/tmp/eXXXXXX") -> "/tmp/e000042" pid number
<<function [[mktemp]](ed.c)>>=
/// main -> <>
char*
mktemp(char *as)
{
    char *s;
    unsigned pid;
    int i;

    pid = getpid();
    s = as;
    while(*s++)
        ;
    s--;

    while(*--s == 'X') {
        *s = pid % 10 + '0';
        pid /= 10;
    }
    s++;

    i = 'a';
    while(access(as, 0) != -1) {
        if(i == 'z')
            return "/";
        *s = i++;
    }
    return as;
}
@
%padism: the cflow /// -> <>, and could have ERROR_NEG1 too

% return "/", argh error would better

% so can have max 26 tmp files per process?

% note that we could delete as part of libc, and also
% we should delete because unsafe because race condition
% for code using it. See goken/include/libc.h note about mkstemp()
% for more info.

\subsection{[[init()]]}
%alt: and [[tfile]]? or just [[init()]]?

% continue init work done in main around zero and tfname
%claude:
[<init()>] creates (or re-creates) the temporary file and resets
[<dot>] and [<dol>] to [<zero>] (empty buffer).
%
It is called both from [[main()]] at startup and from the [[e]] command
(see Section~\ref{sec:command-e}),
which is why it closes the previous [<tfile>] first.

<<function [[init]](ed.c)>>=
/// main | commands('e') -> <>
void
init(void)
{
    <<[[init()]](ed.c) locals>>

    close(tfile);
    <<[[init()]](ed.c) initializing globals>>
    tfile = create(tfname, ORDWR, 0600);
    if(tfile < 0){
        error_1(T);
        exits(nil);
    }
    dot = dol = zero;
}
@
% use tfname set just before in main()
% dot = dol = zero! important too. zero malloced just before in main()
% tfile is set to -1, and close does not raise exn and return value not checked so fine.

<<[[init()]](ed.c) initializing globals>>=
tline = 2;
@

%claude:
Recall that [[tline]] is a Rune-unit offset into [<tfile>] (the
actual byte file offset on disk is [[tline*sizeof(Rune)]]; see the on-disk
layout in Section~\ref{sec:actual-disk-layout}).
%
It starts at~2, not~0, to satisfy two invariants every line offset
must maintain: it must be non-zero so~0 stays the ``no line''
{\em sentinel}, and it must be even so the low bit of each [[zero]]
entry stays free for [<global()>] and the [[k]] command to use as
a ``matched'' flag (see Section~\ref{sec:low-bit}).
%ocaml: too clever abuse int like that! too smart for its own good. simpler in oed
% with proper record (mutable) type

In most of this appendix I will not comment much the error management
code, which is often trivial (but important). 
%
See Section~\ref{sec:error-management} for a full discussion
about error management in [[ed]] and for the code of [<error_1()>]
called in [[init()]] above.

<<globals ed.c>>=
char    T[] = "TMP";
@


\subsection{[[quit()]]}

[<quit()>] implements the ``are you sure?'' safety net.
%
It is called both from [[main()]] after [<commands()>] finished, 
or from [[commands()]] itself when the user types the command [[q]] or [[Q]]
(see Section~\ref{sec:command-q}).
%claude:
If there are unsaved changes ([[fchange == true]]) and the buffer
is non-empty (using the cryptic [[dol!=zero]]), the first [[q]] 
prints [[?]] and resets [[fchange]], so a second [[q]] will actually exit.
%
The [[Q]] command bypasses
this by clearing [[fchange]] before calling [<quit()>]
(see Section~\ref{sec:command-q}).

<<globals ed.c>>=
bool fchange;
@

<<function [[quit]](ed.c)>>=
/// main | commands('q') | commands('Q') | ... -> <>
void
quit(void)
{
    if(vflag && fchange && dol!=zero) {
        fchange = false;
        error(Q);
    }
    // else
    remove(tfname);
    exits(nil);
}
@
%padism: // else (but here subtle because of error())

Note that [<error()>] internally uses [[longjmp()]] to emulate
exceptions in C (see Section~\ref{sec:error-management}), which
is why the control leaves [[quit()]] after the call to [[error()]].

<<globals ed.c>>=
char    Q[] = "";
@
% I introduced this []? because rodata pb otherwise?
% but why need to modify the string?


%******************************************************************************
\section{Displaying and reading text}
%******************************************************************************

%trans:
We have now seen the code of the [<init()>] and [<quit()>] functions.
It remains to see the most important one, [<commands()>] called also
directly from [[main()]].
%
However, it is useful to see before the routines to display and read text
(which are different from the routines to read and write files,
which we will see later).

\subsection{Displaying text}

%claude:
All diagnostic text output in [[ed]]
(e.g., error messages, number of bytes written with the command [[w]])
goes through a small buffering layer:
[<putchr()>] is supposed to print a single Rune but actually accumulates
the UTF-8 encoded bytes in the [<line>] buffer and
flushes with a single [[write()]] call when it sees a newline
(or the buffer is nearly full).
%
[<putst()>] and [<putshst()>] below are wrappers for printing
[[char]] (UTF-8) strings and [[Rune]] strings respectively
and printing a final newline.


% putstr = put string, sp = string pointer?
<<function [[putstr]](ed.c)>>=
/// commands | getfile | error_1 | ... -> <> 
void
putst(char *sp)
{
    Rune r;

    col = 0;
    for(;;) {
        sp += chartorune(&r, sp);
        if(r == 0)
            break;
        putchr(r);
    }
    putchr(L'\n');
}
@
% chartorune!
% char* here is not array for single UTF8 char but instead a series of UTF8 chars

%alt: col? could reset it at the end instead? more logical after putchr the \n


% put sh st ?? similar to putst, but not char, Rune this time
<<function [[putshst]](ed.c)>>=
void
putshst(Rune *sp)
{
    col = 0;
    while(*sp)
        putchr(*sp++);
    putchr(L'\n');
}
@


%grrr: int vs Rune. ac means? why not use Rune?
%claude:
%[<putchr()>] buffers output in [<line>] and flushes on newline
%or when the buffer is nearly full.

<<function [[putchr]](ed.c)>>=
/// error | putst | putshst | ... -> <>
void
putchr(int ac)
{
    char *lp;
    int c;
    Rune rune;

    lp = linp;
    c = ac;
    <<[[putchr()]] if [[listf]]>>

    rune = c;
    lp += runetochar(lp, &rune);

    if(c == '\n' || lp >= &line[sizeof(line)-5]) {
        linp = line;
        // the actual output syscall!
        write(oflag? STDERR: STDOUT, line, lp-line);
        return;
    }
    // else
    linp = lp;
}
@
%grrr: and this time runetochar, argh why int ac -> int c -> Rune r ...
%padism: those // else comment

% runetochar(), and chartorune(), seems a bit weird to convert if convert back.

% actual IO with write syscall accept UTF8 chars, not Rune.

%claude:
%The [[-5]] margin in the
%comparison accounts for the worst case of [[runetochar()]]:
%a single rune can expand to up to 4~bytes in UTF-8, so the
%check must leave room for one full multi-byte character plus
%the possibility that [[lp]] already advanced past the check.

%claude: %example:
The picture below shows [<line>] mid-fill during
a call to [[putshst(L"hello µs")]].
%
The key points:
[<line>] is a flat [[char]] array holding raw UTF-8 bytes
(not [[Rune]] cells, unlike [<tfile>] or [<linebuf>]), so a single
codepoint may occupy one to four cells; [<linp>] is the persistent
fill pointer carried across calls (the local [[lp]] above is initialized
from it and advanced by [[runetochar()]] before the bounds check
fires).
% and the trailing five-byte zone is the high-water margin
% that absorbs whatever [[runetochar()]] just wrote past the previous check.

%claude:
\begin{vdiagram}
   line[]  (flat char[] of raw UTF-8 bytes; here `µ' = U+03BC
            = bytes 0xCE 0xBC, so it spans 2 cells):
   +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+...---+---+---+---+---+---+
   | h | e | l | l | o |   |CE |BC |   |   |   |   |      |   |   |   |   |   |
   +---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+---+...---+---+---+---+---+---+
                           \-µ-/
   ^                               ^                      ^
   line                            linp                   line+sizeof(line)-5
                                                         |<--- worst-case --->|
                                                          4-byte UTF-8 rune
                                                            + safety margin
\end{vdiagram}

%claude:
[<linp>] tracks how full the buffer is. The flush check
[[lp >= &line[sizeof(line)-5]]] reserves 5~bytes at the end of
the buffer because: (1)~runes converted to UTF-8 can be up to 4~bytes each,
%(``hello~$\mu$s'' ends with a 2-byte rune that
%[[runetochar()]] writes after [[lp]] is checked), 
and (2)~one extra byte for safety.
%
Without this margin, a multi-byte rune
arriving when the buffer is nearly full could overrun the array.


% but putchr is really used for display, not for editing
%claude:
Note the [[oflag]] check: when [[-o]] is active, the edited content
goes to [[STDOUT]], so diagnostic output from [<putchr()>] is
redirected to [[STDERR]] to avoid corrupting the data stream.

\subsection{Reading text}
%alt: Reading characters

%claude:
Character input from the user
%to enter commands or text
is layered through [<getchr()>], which checks three sources in order:
(1) [<peekc>], a one-character pushback used when a character needs
to be ``unread'' (a classic technique used in many lexers in \plan);
(2) [<globp>], a programmed command string (e.g., [[L"r"]] or [[L"a"]]
injected by [[main()]]);
%said-later: and later by global() and g command, hence its name (said in comment below)
(3) actual console input via [[Bgetrune()]] (from [[libbio]], see \book{Libcore}).
%
This layering is what makes the [[globp]] trick work---[<commands()>]
does not need to know whether input comes from the user or from
a synthetic command.

<<globals ed.c>>=
//option<Rune> (0 = None)
int peekc;
@
% classic lexer vars you need when not using lex
%grrr: why not use Rune?

<<globals ed.c>>=
//option<Rune> (0 = None)
int lastc;
@
%grrr: why not use Rune??


<<globals ed.c>>=
// optional programmed command (e.g., L"r", L"a" or longer string with global())
//option<array<Rune>>
Rune*   globp;
@
%alt: move to later and aspectize it? no need to understand early the globp = "r"!

%grrr: int vs char vs rune
<<function [[getchr]](ed.c)>>=
int
getchr(void)
{
    lastc = peekc;
    if(lastc) {
        peekc = 0;
        return lastc;
    }
    // else
    if(globp) {
        lastc=*globp++;
        if(lastc != 0)
            return lastc;
        // else
        globp = nil;
        return EOF;
    }
    // else
    lastc = Bgetrune(&bcons);
    return lastc;
}
@
