%claude:
[<gettty()>]\footnote{``get from teletype'', an old \unix name for the console},
reads a line of user input (via [<gety()>]) and checks
for the special [[.\n]] terminator that ends text-entry mode
in commands like [[a]] and [[i]] (see Section~\ref{sec:ed-tutorial-session}).

% rc = return code. 0 means ok (read more lines in append), pos = error
% see append() fn interface
<<function [[gettty]](ed.c)>>=
/// main -> commands('a'|'i') -> add -> append(<>,...) -> <>
int
gettty(void)
{
    int rc;

    rc = gety();
    if(rc)
        return rc;
    // else
    if(linebuf[0] == '.' && linebuf[1] == 0)
        return EOF;
    // else
    return OK_0; // OK_0 for caller to read more lines
}
@
%padism: OK_0 but really needed here
%grrr:
%padism: more complex cflow annotation -> -> <>
%alt: move linebuf[] here as it's first time used?

% 0 means continue (read more lines) vs EOF means stop, interface required by append()
% positive means error. (EOF is negative?)

<<constants ed.c>>=
EOF = -1,
@
% tricky constant, in oed I had pbs with it when return it vs when not


Note that there is no easy way in [[ed]] to create a line containing just
a [['.']] followed by a newline since this special sequence is recognized
by [[gettty()]] to mark the end of a user input.
%
One needs instead to enter some fake text like [['.A']] and then use a
substitute command to remove the [['A']]. Fortunately, it is rare to need text
with a single dot by itself in a line (which is probably why this special sequence
was chosen).
% no escape mechanism

[<gety()>] does the actual character-by-character reading into
[<linebuf>], stopping at a newline.

% gety (and gettty), will modify linebuf for the caller (and return OK_0 or EOF or err)
<<function [[gety]](ed.c)>>=
/// gettty -> <>
int
gety(void)
{
    int c;
    Rune *p = linebuf;
    <<[[gety()]] other locals>>

    for(;;) {
        c = getchr();
        if(c == '\n') {
            *p = 0;
            return OK_0;
        }
        // else
        if(c == EOF) {
            <<[[get()]] if [[gf]]>>
            return c;
        }
        // else
        if(c == 0)
            continue;
        // else
        *p++ = c;
        if(p >= &linebuf[LBSIZE-sizeof(Rune)])
            error(Q);
    }
}
@
