%******************************************************************************
\section{[[commands()]] interpreter loop}
%******************************************************************************

%trans: 
We are now finally ready to see the code of [<commands()>], the main
command interpreter loop.
%claude:
In the infinite [[for]] loop below,
[[commands()]] reads first an optional {\em address range} into [<addr1>],[<addr2>]
and then dispatches on the command character [[c]] via a [[switch]].
%
As we will see soon, most command [[switch]] cases end with a [[continue]] to
loop back;
falling through to [[error(Q)]] below after the switch deals with unknown commands.

<<function [[commands]](ed.c)>>=
void
commands(void)
{
    int c;
    <<[[commands()]] other locals>>

    for(;;) {
        <<[[commands()]] in for loop, if [[pflag]]>>
        <<[[commands()]] read [[addr1]] and [[c]] via [[getchr]]>>
        switch(c) {
        <<[[commands()]] switch [[c]] cases (ed.c)>>
        }
        error(Q);
    }
}
@
% error(Q) show later, but essentially just jump to before commands() ?
% but why we need error? for(;;) not enough? because the commands
% are using 'continue' so the error is the default when not continue
% (but bad I think)
%grrr: int c, but char really, or Rune at least

I will defer the explanations about address ranges to
Section~\ref{sec:command-addresses} but for now it is enough
to understand that some commands can operate on ranges (as in [[1,3p]])
and that the two globals below will store the starting and ending
part of the command address range. They both point to
[<zero>] entries, similar to [<dot>] and [<dol>] we saw before.

<<globals ed.c>>=
// ref<int> in zero[]
int*    addr1;
// ref<int> in zero[]
int*    addr2;
@
% note that some commands like 'r' (and setwide) will set those too,
% not just interactive (hence given global later)


One of the command [[switch]] cases handles the [[EOF]] character returned
by [<getchr()>] when there is no more input (e.g., when the user typed [[Ctrl-D]]).
In that case [[commands()]] simply returns to the caller [[main()]] which
will then call [[quit()]].
% can also get EOF with globp when globp finished
% and also EOF when pipe or >>! finished in script.

<<[[commands()]] switch [[c]] cases (ed.c)>>=
case EOF:
    return;
@


%******************************************************************************
\section{[[r]]eading a file: [[r]]}
%******************************************************************************
\label{sec:reading-r}
%spirit: quite tricky, quite long, lots of subsections here.

%claude: %trans:
Reading a file (as in [[r foo.txt]]) is the first substantial command,
%toc:
and it involves several cooperating functions:
[<filename()>] parses the filename argument in [<file>],
[<setwide()>] sets the address range to the whole buffer
(which will have for effect to add the content of [[foo.txt]] to
the end of [[zero]], after [<dol>]),
[<append()>] inserts lines by calling a callback in a loop,
[<getfile()>] (the callback) reads one line from the input file
(e.g., [[foo.txt]])
into [<linebuf>], and [<putline()>] writes [[linebuf]] to [<tfile>]
and returns the offset to store in [<zero>].

% globp = "r" = automatic command to do first = read file! important command
%  rarely called explicitely, but important nonetheless

<<globals ed.c>>=
char    file[FNSIZE];
@
% seen savedfile[] before, initialized when running ed foo.txt
% but here it's not really a global; it's something returned really
% by filename() and then used in getfile()

<<globals ed.c>>=
fdt io;
Biobuf  iobuf;
@
%padism: fdt again


<<[[commands()]] switch [[c]] cases (ed.c)>>=
case 'r':
    // will set file[]
    filename(c);
